file-name: XC429022-calls of a juvenile Barn Swallow and some calls from its parents Harper's Island 28th July 2018_HH_1.mp3
rmk: Begging calls from a fledged juvenile Barn Swallow inside in the observation hide at Harper's Island, with calls from its attending parents also. High pass filter applied below 2kHz because of the low background drone of traffic, which still detracts from the recording somewhat.

The clip is edited from several minutes of sounds made by two young Swallows that were sitting on a cottage roof. At least one parent was 'keeping an eye' on them and (probably) occasionally arriving to feed them.  I did not see any of the activity as I left the recorder and then played back the result. The opening ten seconds contain a burst of calls that accompanied the youngsters flying off [0:02]. This was when I left the recorder on the cottage roof, thereby disturbing them. At some point, a Wren landed on the roof and it must have perched right beside the recorder because its song is loud and clear at 0:10. After that, the Wren changes perch and the subsequent song-bursts are not so close. From 0:30, the young Swallows are resting on the roof and making typical twitters - the sound of offspring hoping to receive food from an incoming parent. It seems that, at around forty seconds, an adult flies in and may have delivered food - the calls become more intense at 0:45. Irrespective of whether the young were fed or not, they fly off at the end of the recording.

The recordings begins with three calls from a passing Chough. The Chough was cruising overhead along the line of a small road. I was out of sight and screened by a barn. I think that the Chough called because it spotted me. In turn, the Swallow (an adult) joined in the commotion. Swallow alarm calls begin at 0:07. Two young Swallows were perched farther away so I assume that the adult was training them to associate the alarm call with humans. Perhaps the Swallow's nest was inside the barn (I did not look inside)  and I was too close for comfort.

loc: Oxford Island, Lough Neagh, Co. Armagh, Northern Ireland
rmk: Alarm calls from several Swallows in the vicinity of nests. As is normal for Swallows, the alarms are delivered for a variety of reasons, not just genuine alarm. The species is an expert at crying wolf! Coots can be heard in the background.
In the hall of the station.

Already three males were singing.
Wind noise has been suppressed.
ID certainty 100%. (Archiv. tape 73 side A track 43 seq. B)
